**Abstract:**
Major essay dated December 3, 1998 titled "On Statements and Statements" opening with Gilson and de Lubac quotations on scholastic philosophism and faith as imperfect knowledge. Comprehensive analysis of Searle's theory of language: speech-acts, meaning, and illocutionary/perlocutionary distinction. Extended critique using examples to show statements function performatively. Develops concept of "practical understanding" incarnated in action vs. Searle's speculative understanding.

**AI Recommendation:** Major book chapter draft; see 98-dec-1-1 and 98-Nov-2 variants.

